#Text=Abraham Fraunce
#Text=Abraham Fraunce ( born between 1558 and 1560 ? – died in 1592 or 1593 ? ) was an English poet .
#Text=Life
#Text=A native of Shropshire , he was born between 1558 and 1560 .
#Text=His name appears in a list of pupils of Shrewsbury School in January 1571 , [ 1 ]
#Text=and he joined St John 's College , Cambridge , in 1576 , becoming a fellow in 1580/1 . [ 2 ]
#Text=His Latin comedy , Victoria , dedicated to Sir Philip Sidney , was probably written at Cambridge , where he remained until he had taken his M.A. degree in 1583 .
#Text=He was called to the bar at Gray 's Inn in 1588 , and then apparently practised as a barrister in the court of the Welsh marches . [ 3 ]
#Text=After the death of his patron , Sidney , Fraunce was protected by Sidney 's sister , Mary Herbert , Countess of Pembroke .
#Text=His last work was published in 1592 . [ 3 ]

#Text=According to the 19th-century antiquary Joseph Hunter in his Chorus Vatum , in 1633 Fraunce wrote an Epithalamium in honour of the marriage of Lady Magdalen Egerton , seventh daughter of the Earl of Bridgwater , in whose service he may have been ; thus , it was long assumed that Fraunce died in or after 1633 .
#Text=More recent scholarship , however , places Fraunce 's death in 1592 or 1593 [ 4 ] and attributes the Cutler-Egerton epithalamium to Abraham Darcie . [ 5 ]
#Text=Works
#Text=His works are :
#Text=The Lamentations of Amintas for the death of Phyllis ( 1587 ) , a version in English hexameters of his friend , Thomas Watson 's , Latin Amyntas
#Text=The Lawiers Logike , exemplifying the praecepts of Logike by the practise of the common Lawe ( 1585 )
#Text=The Arcadian Rhetorike ( 1588 )
#Text=Abrahami Fransi Insignium , Armorum ...
#Text=explicatio
#Text=The Countess of Pembroke 's Yvychurch ( 1591/2 ) , containing a translation of Tasso 's Aminta , a reprint of his earlier version of Watson

#Text=The Lamentation of Corydon for the love of Alexis ( Virgil , eclogue II ) , a short translation from Heliodorus , and , in the third part ( 1592 ) " Aminta 's Dale , " a collection of " conceited tales " supposed to be related by the nymphs of Ivychurch

column1: #Text=The Countess of Pembroke 's Emanuell ( 1591 )
#Text=The Third Part of Pembroke 's Ivychurch , entitled Aminta 's Dale ( 1592 )
#Text=Victoria , a Latin Comedy ( written before or in 1583 ; not published until 1906 ) .
#Text=It is a translation of Luigi Pasqualigo 's play , Il Fedele . [ 6 ]

#Text=The Arcadian Rhetorike owes much to earlier critical treatises , but has a special interest from its references to Edmund Spenser , and Fraunce quotes from the Faerie Queene a year before the publication of the first books .
#Text=In Colin Clouts Come Home Again , Spenser speaks of Fraunce as Corydon , on account of his translations of Virgil 's second eclogue .
#Text=His poems are written in classical metres , and he was regarded by his contemporaries as the best exponent of Gabriel Harvey 's theory .
#Text=Even Thomas Nashe had a good word for " sweete Master Fraunce " . [ 3 ]

#Text=The Countess of Pembroke 's Emanuell , hexameters on the nativity and passion of Christ , with versions of some psalms , were reprinted by Alexander Grosart in the third volume of his Miscellanies of the Fuller Worthies ’ Library ( 1872 ) .

#Text=Joseph Hunter in his Chorus Vatum stated that five of Fraunce 's songs were included in Sidney 's Astrophel and Stella , but these should probably be attributed not to Fraunce , but to Thomas Campion .

#Text=See a life prefixed to the transcription of a manuscript Latin comedy by Fraunce , Victoria , by Professor GC Moore Smith , published in W Bang 's Materialien zur Kunde des älteren Englischen Dramas , vol. xiv , 1906 . [ 3 ]
#Text=Dana Sutton argues that Fraunce may be the author of Hymenaeus ( 1578 ) . [ 7 ]
